<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n36201e"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36201e">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36201e"> 201(e)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> falchion</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">I swear to thee, worthy reader, if history and tradition belie not this warrior <font color="green">[General Van Poffenbiurgh]</font>, I would give all the money in my pocket to have seen him accoutred <i>cap-&agrave;-pie</i>,&mdash;booted to the middle, sashed to the chin, crowned with an overshadowing cocked hat, and girded with a leathern belt ten inches broad, from which trailed a <mark>falchion</mark>, of a length I dare not mention. <small> Washington Irving, <a name="WINY" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#WINY"><cite title="source">A History of New York, by Diedrich Knickerbocker</cite></a> (ed. unknown) 254</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: A falchion (from L. <i>falx</i>, a sickle) is is a one-handed, single-edged sword of European origin, whose design is reminiscent of the Chinese <i>dadao</i>, and modern machete. </mm> </dd></dl>
